Data

For this assignment, we will use data from a study on elephants and the effects of poaching on tusk size.

Reference: Chiyo, Patrick I., Vincent Obanda, and David K. Korir. Illegal tusk harvest and the decline of tusk size in the African elephant. Ecology and Evolution 5, 22: 52165229 (2015). Data deposited at Dryad Digital Repository.

1. Before starting data analysis, read the abstract of the paper to get an idea of the questions being asked. In 2-3 sentences, describe what the study is testing and the variables involved.

The study is testing the effects of African elephant tusk harvesting on tusk size and evolution. The variables involved are tusk length, size, and circumference along with age. The study is also testing whether or not the poaching of larger tusks from the African elephants was a driver of smaller tusk evolution in future generations and whether or not the trait was heritable.

8. What is the mean, median, and standard deviation for age of males and females included in the study? Separate the results by year of sample collection. Does the sampling look even between years and sexes?

elephants %>%
  select(sex, estimated_age_years, years_of_sample_collection) %>%
  filter(sex=="m") %>%
  summarize(sex, years_of_sample_collection,
            mean_age_m=mean(estimated_age_years, na.rm = T),
            median_age_m=median(estimated_age_years, na.rm = T),
            sd_age_m=sd(estimated_age_years, na.rm = T)) %>%
  distinct()

9. Is age (independent variable) a positive predictor of tusk length (dependent variable)? Create a plot that shows the relationship between these variables and add a linear model fit line.

elephants %>%
  select(estimated_age_years, tusk_length_in_cm) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=estimated_age_years, y=tusk_length_in_cm)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F) +
  scale_y_log10() +
  labs(title= "The Relationship between Age and Tusk Length in African Elephants", x="Age (y)", y="Tusk Length (cm)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 182 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_smooth()`).
## Warning: Removed 182 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

Yes, age is a positive predictor of tusk length as we can see with the positive trend of both the data and the linear trendline.

11. The authors argue that because poachers preferentially target elephants with large tusks, this has resulted in a decrease in average tusk length. Is this supported by the data? Show your code and calculations below.

names(elephants)
## [1] "years_of_sample_collection" "elephant_id"               
## [3] "sex"                        "estimated_age_years"       
## [5] "shoulder_height_in_cm"      "tusk_length_in_cm"         
## [7] "tusk_circumference_in_cm"
elephants %>%
  group_by(years_of_sample_collection) %>%
  summarize(mean_tusk_length=mean(tusk_length_in_cm, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=years_of_sample_collection, y=mean_tusk_length)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill=years_of_sample_collection)) +
  labs(title="Average Tusk Length over Time", x="Sample Periods", y="Average Tusk Length")

12. Male elephants reach effective sexual maturity at 25 years while females are sexually mature at 12 years. Make a new dataframe that extracts only the males and females at sexual maturity. Then, make a plot that shows the range of tusk length between the two sample periods for these mature elephants.

mature_elephants <- elephants %>%
  select(sex, estimated_age_years, tusk_length_in_cm, years_of_sample_collection) %>%
  filter(sex=="m" & estimated_age_years>=25 | sex == "f" & estimated_age_years>=12) 
 ggplot(data = mature_elephants,
        mapping=aes(x=years_of_sample_collection, y=tusk_length_in_cm)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=sex)) +
  labs(title = "Range of Tusk Lengths within Male and Female Elephants at Sexual Maturity", x = "Sample Periods", y="Tusk Length (cm)")
